  "What is the Internal Rate of Return (IRR)?": "",
  "The total return on investment over its lifetime": "",
  "The discount rate that makes the net present value of all cash flows from an investment equal to zero": "",
  "The average annual profit divided by the initial investment": "",
  "The interest rate charged on a loan": "",
  "IRR is the annualized rate of return that sets NPV to zero. It represents the project's true percentage return, accounting for the time value of money and the pattern of cash flows.": "",
  "What is a hurdle rate?": "",
  "The highest return ever achieved by a company": "",
  "The minimum rate of return a project must achieve to be accepted": "",
  "The average market return over the past decade": "",
  "The risk-free rate set by the Federal Reserve": "",
  "The hurdle rate is the minimum acceptable rate of return for an investment. Projects with IRR above the hurdle rate are accepted; those below are rejected. It typically equals or exceeds the company's cost of capital.": "",
  "What is the payback period?": "",
  "The time until the first cash flow is received": "",
  "The time it takes for cumulative cash inflows to equal the initial investment": "",
  "The total lifespan of the project": "",
  "The number of years until the project's IRR equals zero": "",
  "The payback period measures how long it takes to recoup the initial investment from cash inflows. It is simple to calculate but ignores the time value of money and cash flows beyond the payback date.": "",
  "What is the discounted payback period?": "",
  "The payback period minus inflation": "",
  "The payback period divided by the discount rate": "",
  "The same as the regular payback period": "",
  "The time until cumulative discounted cash flows equal the initial investment, incorporating the time value of money": "",
  "The discounted payback period improves upon the simple payback by discounting each cash flow before accumulating them. It tells you how long until you recover your investment in present-value terms.": "",
  "What does the IRR 'reinvestment assumption' mean?": "",
  "IRR implicitly assumes that intermediate cash flows earn the same rate as the IRR when reinvested": "",
  "No reinvestment of cash flows is assumed": "",
  "All profits must be reinvested in the same project": "",
  "Cash flows are assumed to be spent immediately": "",
  "The IRR calculation implicitly assumes that all cash flows received during the project are reinvested at the IRR rate. This can be problematic when the IRR is very high, since finding equally profitable reinvestment opportunities may be unrealistic.": "",
  "What are 'non-conventional cash flows'?": "",
  "Cash flows in foreign currency": "",
  "Cash flows that occur monthly instead of annually": "",
  "Cash flows that switch from negative to positive (or vice versa) more than once during a project's life": "",
  "Cash flows that are unusually large": "",
  "Non-conventional cash flows change signs multiple times (e.g., negative initial cost, positive operating cash flows, then a negative decommissioning cost). These can produce multiple IRR solutions, making IRR unreliable.": "",
  "What is the 'scale problem' with IRR?": "",
  "IRR cannot be calculated for large investments": "",
  "Large projects always have lower IRR": "",
  "The scale of the graph affects IRR interpretation": "",
  "IRR ignores project size, so a small project with high IRR may create less total value than a large project with lower IRR": "",
  "Since IRR is a percentage, it does not reflect the dollar amount of value created. A 30% return on $1,000 ($300) creates far less wealth than a 15% return on $1,000,000 ($150,000).": "",
  "What does Yield to Maturity (YTM) represent for a bond?": "",
  "The annual interest payment divided by face value": "",
  "The annualized return if the bond is held to maturity, accounting for coupon payments, face value, and current price": "",
  "The return earned in the first year only": "",
  "The coupon rate printed on the bond": "",
  "YTM is the total annualized return expected from a bond if held to maturity. It is the IRR of the bond's cash flows -- the rate that equates the PV of all coupons and the face value to the current market price.": "",
  "What does MIRR stand for, and how does it differ from IRR?": "",
  "Minimum Internal Rate of Return -- it calculates the worst-case scenario": "",
  "Marginal Internal Rate of Return -- it measures the return on the last dollar invested": "",
  "Modified Internal Rate of Return -- it uses the cost of capital for reinvestment instead of the IRR itself": "",
  "Maximum Internal Rate of Return -- it selects the highest possible IRR": "",
  "MIRR (Modified Internal Rate of Return) addresses IRR's unrealistic reinvestment assumption by assuming intermediate cash flows are reinvested at the cost of capital, not at the IRR. It provides a single, unique solution even with non-conventional cash flows.": "",
  "Together, NPV, IRR, and payback period provide what kind of information?": "",
  "Redundant information -- only one metric is needed": "",
  "Complementary perspectives: NPV gives dollar value, IRR gives percentage return, and payback gives time to recovery": "",
  "Only one useful metric while the others are obsolete": "",
  "Conflicting answers that confuse decision-making": "",
  "These three metrics complement each other: NPV tells you how much value is created (dollars), IRR tells you the rate of return (percentage), and payback tells you how quickly you recover your investment (time). Together, they provide a comprehensive picture.": "",
